UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199685900376
AB  - This paper explores the welfare effects of capital inflows when some imports are subject to quantitative restrictions. It is shown that in a Heckscher-Ohlin model where all imports are restricted by quotas and some fraction of the initial domestic capital stock is foreign owned, a capital inflow is welfare improving regardless of the ranking of sectoral factor intensities. With sector-specific capital stocks and both tariff-ridden and quota restricted imports, the consequences of direct foreign investment in any sector are uncertain and depend upon whether the two imports are compensated substitutes or complements as well as the characteristics of production.
ER  - 

